<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JAN 94 / Government may review its use of private consultants
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government is considering launching a wide-ranging review of how
departments award consultancy work, which is estimated to be worth more than
Pounds 100m a year.
The Cabinet Office's efficiency unit is looking at whether private
consultants are giving taxpayers value for money, how consultants are
appointed and whether there is scope to make the system more competitive,
according to a senior official.
Whitehall departments are increasingly taking on management consultants,
merchant banks and accountants as outside advisers on big projects.
In many cases the government is the biggest customer of private
consultancies.
Senior civil servants from all government departments which use outside
consultancies, such as the Treasury and the Department of Trade and
Industry, would be involved in any review.
An investigation into the use of the private consultancies would be the
government's strongest response to date to criticism that lucrative private
contracts are often made on an ad hoc basis.
An increasing number of government departments have taken to hiring merchant
banks and accountants. The DTI for example, hired Kleinwort Benson, the UK
merchant bank, and KPMG Peat Marwick, the accountants, to advise it over the
future of the Post Office, while the Department for Education recently took
on Rothschild, another UK merchant bank, to look at ways of attracting
private investment.
Whitehall officials predict that the government's determination to break new
ground in developing public sector projects with private finance and to
contract many services to the private sector as part of its market testing
programme will lead to more contracts for consultancies.
'The efficiency unit is already looking at whether these consultancies offer
value for money' said a Whitehall official.
Private companies have also been used to advise government on significant
political changes, such as the reform of the National Health Service, which
has seen a large increase in the use of consultancies.
</TEXT>
