<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JAN 94 / India rejects Pakistan's attempt to link bilateral dialogue
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SHIRAZ SIDVHA
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW DELHI
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
India yesterday rejected Pakistan's attempt to link bilateral dialogue to a
change in New Delhi's stand on the Kashmir issue and cautioned Pakistan that
this might cause a delay in settling other bilateral problems such as the
Siachen glacier, the demarcation of a maritime boundary in the Sir Creek
area, nuclear non-proliferation, and stabilisation along the line of control
between the two countries, Shiraz Sidvha reports from New Delhi.
Mr JN Dixit, India's foreign secretary, told a press conference yesterday
that a stalemate on the Kashmir issue had not been broken during talks with
Pakistani officials which concluded in Islamabad on Monday.
Indo-Pakistan relations could not be viewed through the prism of the Kashmir
issue alone, he said, and India was prepared to continue bilateral
discussions as long as no pre-conditions were set. Mr Dixit said India had
earlier planned to send proposals within two weeks which could result in the
resolution of almost all outstanding issues between the two countries. These
might be delayed, with Islamabad virtually rejecting India's proposal to
hold the next round of foreign secretary-level talks in four months.
