<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JAN 94 / London Stock Exchange: Equity futures and options trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERRY BYLAND
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Derivatives markets continued to exert a powerful influence over the
underlying stock market yesterday, writes Terry Byland.
But stock index futures were themselves highly volatile as locals, or
independent traders, tried to anticipate the expected bout of profit-taking
in the March contract on the FT-SE 100 Index. There was also continued
nervousness over expiry on over the counter programmes.
The March futures contract ignored a firm opening in equities and fell
sharply as the locals sold it down relentlessly until it stood at a small
discount against the index itself - fair value now stands at around 13
points. Selling pressure also came from the US, where investors feared that
interest rates may rise.
In what has become a rare response, London securities firms opened
'negative' basket programmes, buying the future and selling the blue chip
stocks. At midsession, however, futures selling died away and the contract
rallied strongly, closing at 3,422, almost in line with fair value. Trading
volume was high at just above 13,000 contracts.
Business in traded options was also strong, at 40,740 contracts, with the
FT-SE 100 option recording 18,658; the half-session on New Year's Eve saw
5,992 Footsie contracts traded. The Euro FT-SE option had 3,571 lots dealt.
Individual contracts were headed by Glaxo, with 2,355 traded as the market
responded to the news on US sales rulings.
Tomkins, Ladbroke and Trafalgar House, favoured in the new year
recommend-ations of several broking houses, had 1,488, 1,129 and 1.016
contracts transacted respectively.
</TEXT>
