<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JAN 94 / Commodities and Agriculture: Russia faces Dollars 1.5bn US
grain credits bill in 1994
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURIE MORSE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Russia must keep up to date on payments falling due this year against
US-backed grain loans to remain eligible to receive new US farm credits, a
senior US official said yesterday.
The payments, against Dollars 1.5bn owed to private banks but guaranteed by
the US Department of Agriculture's Commodity Credit Corporation, start
falling due this week and extend through the year.
Mr Chris Goldthwait, the USDA's general sales manager, said yesterday that
so long as Russia remained current on its existing loan repayments it was
technically eligible to receive new credits. However, the Russians have
appeared to be cautious about increasing their debt for food purchases. 'The
Russians have not requested further credit guarantees,' Mr Goldthwait said.
'In recent discussions, they have indicated that they would rather make
their purchases with cash.'
Russia spent much of 1993 in default on its US grain loans but became
current at the end of the year through a series of payments arranged as part
of the Paris Club's rescheduling of the country's overall foreign debt. A
final Dollars 147.4m payment was made to the USDA last week. Russia's total
debt to the USDA, including the Dollars 1.5bn due in 1994, is about Dollars
3.5bn.
Grain traders hopes that President Clinton will offer a combination of farm
credits and aid when he meets President Boris Yeltsin later this month are
waning.
Wheat futures for March delivery at the Chicago Board of Trade jumped more
than 8 cents a 60lb bushel yesterday on news that China, long absent from
the US market, had bid for 1.1m tonnes of US soft red winter wheat under the
Export Enhancement Programme. The wheat would be delivered to China during
January and February.
Traders said that China's bid - Dollars 88.50 a tonne - would require a
subsidy of as much as Dollars 60 a tonne at current prices. The results of
the USDA tender are expected today.
</TEXT>
