<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JAN 94 / MCI puts Dollars 2bn into local challenge
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MCI Communications, the US long-distance telephone company, yesterday
announced a Dollars 2bn (Pounds 1.3bn) initiative to compete with America's
Baby Bell local phone companies.
It is also stepping up investment in its information super-highway - the
network needed to transmit huge amounts of data at high speed.
The company said that it and 'associated partners' were expected to invest
more than Dollars 20bn over the next six years to deliver new long-distance
and local communications services to businesses, homes and research
institutions, under the brand-name networkMCI.
MCI played a central role in forcing competition into the US long-distance
telephone market. Its entry into the local arena could spell tough
competition for the Baby Bells.
Yesterday's announcement was the clearest indication so far of MCI's
long-range strategy in America's information revolution, which is blurring
the boundaries between the telecommunications, computer and television
industries - as well as the regulatory and legal divisions between
long-distance and local telephone companies.
Even so, the company left many important details unclear, including the
names of its potential partners and just how much they would contribute.
Mr Bert Roberts, the chairman, noted that last summer's global alliance with
British Telecommunications, which is investing Dollars 4.3bn in MCI in
return for a 20 per cent stake, was helping MCI to finance its capital
spending.
The most dramatic element of MCI's strategy is its plan to compete against
the local telephone companies, as one of a number of so-called Competitive
Access Providers (Caps), which operate fibre optic networks in cities,
creaming off lucrative business customers.
MCI already owns a subsidiary, acquired in 1990 from Western Union, which
has telecoms access to more than 2,000 office buildings. It is to give this
business, renamed MCI Metro, a boost by investing Dollars 2bn in fibre optic
cable rings and modern traffic switching facilities, initially in 20
metropolitan areas. The company may later target household consumers.
Lex, Page 14
</TEXT>
