<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JAN 94 / The Lex Column: Williams Holdings
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
On its own, the acquisition of Corbin &amp; Russwin, the US locksmith, will
hardly transform Williams. Yet the Pounds 50m deal, completed on new year's
eve, brings the group's acquisitions for last year to nearly Pounds 140m.
Taken together with the recent sale of its engineering businesses, Williams
thus seems less trapped by its balance sheet than some of its critics have
claimed. Though sale of the electronics businesses and its Fairey bridge
builders will have to wait, the group has made progress in adjusting its
focus on to a limited range of businesses with a reasonable strategic fit.
Corbin, for example, will double Williams' share of the US commercial lock
market to 20 per cent, creating a stronger base from which to attack the
market leader, Ingersoll-Rand.
In the final quarter of 1993, Williams' shares outperformed Hanson by 10 per
cent and BTR by 15 per cent. This relative re-rating does not necessarily
mean Williams can now relax. The Corbin acquisition will both absorb cash
and involve a goodwill hit of some Pounds 30m, so that gearing will rise to
60 per cent. Williams may rail against those on the Accounting Standards
Board who still believe goodwill should be written off. But even with eight
times interest cover, such gearing leaves little leeway for acquisitions to
complete the transformation process. It will help if the company's full-year
figures show its cash generation has improved as the use of acquisition
provisions has come down.
</TEXT>
