<DATE>940105
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JAN 94 / The Lex Column: Capital connections
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
If the multimedia hype continues, phone company executives may soon have to
stop talking telephone numbers and start spending them. MCI's announcement
yesterday of Dollars 20bn-worth of strategic plans falls mostly into the
talk category - the investment in long distance super-highways and local
capacity will be phased, shared with partners and is partly an upgrading of
existing facilities.
The gambit is also politically inspired; MCI wants to cut the amount it pays
local phone companies for its final connection to consumers, so threatening
to compete with them is a useful spur.
Still, even with the rhetoric stripped away, it does point towards the high
capital investment that phone companies will need. AT&amp;T and MCI may well
move from long distance traffic to compete for local calls. While that
investment would be costly, there is little doubt that the Baby Bells'
monopoly margins could be cut. That, however, would probably prompt the
regulator to open the US long distance market to local companies, increasing
competition and cutting margins there too.
Several expensive fibre-optic super-highways may be built, providing the US
with vast capacity. As such systems could carry almost limitless traffic,
phone companies will struggle to avoid prices falling to commodity levels.
Some value-added services will help maintain margins, and even if video
conferencing becomes as cheap as using the fax, network operators will
benefit from the increased usage of their systems. Yet phone companies will
be relying on lower prices stimulating demand in order to recoup most of
their capital spending.
MCI's strategy is a sensible response to the development of real competition
in US telecoms, but shareholders may yet view the old cosy cartel with
nostalgia.
</TEXT>
