<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JAN 94 / Management: Mysterious case of the vanishing career ladder -
Tomorrow's bosses are being left to find their own way to the top
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LUCY KELLAWAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Once upon a time managers spent their careers climbing the company ladder a
step at a time, in a straight line towards the top.
The upward journey taken by today's managers is more circuitous. Now that
the old corporate hierarchies have been dismantled, the ladders have gone
and it is often unclear what counts as the next step up.
Moreover, in many companies there is no longer a paternalistic personnel
department showing ambitious employees the way. Now that everybody is
'empowered', they are meant to 'own' - ie be responsible for - everything,
including their careers.
This laissez-faire approach to nurturing tomorrow's managers came under
attack at a recent seminar in London attended by personnel directors of
large British companies.
According to Andrew Mayo, director of human resource development at ICL,
many aspiring high-fliers are getting lost, and may even be leaving their
jobs because they feel stuck. 'I listen to people who say that 'there used
to be five slots between me and the top. Now I can't see the way forward, so
I've decided to go outside'.'
A survey conducted by GHN, the management consultancy which hosted the
seminar, shows that 19 out of 20 companies believe it is important to
develop high-fliers. Yet half do so passively, arguing that the full
responsibility for career progression should rest with the individual, not
with the company. Indeed, many of these companies now frown on the very word
'career', preferring instead the vaguer euphemism 'personal development'.
Yet the task for which top managers are being groomed - or grooming
themselves - is increasingly onerous. The days when someone could rise
through a single department such as marketing or finance and emerge at the
top, are gone. Business leaders need broad experience of different
functions, and different markets. They need strategic vision, political
skills, communication skills, team leading skills, a clarity of mind as well
as the ability to change and be flexible. It is a tall order.
Mayo argues that companies wanting to help equip managers for such a role
must intervene to make sure that the right training and experience is going
to the right sort of people. 'If you want to develop true general managers
you need to help them and make interventions.'
He also argues that if you leave it to the aspiring managers themselves you
may miss some people with real potential. He says the laissez-faire approach
penalises women: 'The kind of person who pushes themselves needs to do it 24
hours a day,' he
explains.
Deciding to intervene is one thing - getting it right is another.
Companies pick out their high fliers in a bewildering variety of ways. Some,
such as Amstrad, have traditionally gone for a seat of the pants evaluation,
leaning heavily on the culture and style of Alan Sugar, the company's
founder.
At the other extreme are the multinationals - IBM or Shell, for example -
which use complicated systems of appraisal, often backed up with high-tech
wizardry, that plot the career profile of individual managers and map that
against the needs of the company.
Having selected the high-fliers, companies develop them through a mixture of
outside training and work experience: and both routes are strewn with
obstacles.
Sheila Forbes of Reed Elsevier argues that companies are too willing to pay
enormous sums on training tomorrow's bosses, sending them to business
schools without any clear idea of what they are getting out of it. 'Often
the standard MBA approach doesn't help. The problem is how you get the
management trainers to work with you, rather than simply adopt an MBA
approach. We need to ask ourselves if we are demanding enough as clients of
the providers of management education'. She says it is a mistake to put
someone through these courses (which might take them out of the office for
two or three months) only to return them to the same job afterwards. 'During
those courses people move on, and they want a new challenge when they come
back.'
Practical problems of moving people around the organisation can be even
greater still. Blue Circle, the building materials group, owns a number of
autonomously-managed companies. It believes that top managers do not make
themselves, and that candidates for the top need experience of different
parts of the group. Without stage managing from the centre it would be
impossible for managers to jump from one subsidiary to another.
To meet its needs, Blue Circle has developed a five-to-ten year management
succession plan, and is moving its hand-picked managers round the world, to
ensure that each will have the right sort of experience for a future at the
top. 'In theory it is simple,' says Peter Mutter, personnel director. 'We
ensure there is enough training so they have a tool bag of skills and then
we supplement that with experience.'
However, the company has found that its subsidiaries blanch when they are
asked to give up their high fliers so that they can get more experience
working for another part of the group.
The answer, says Mutter, is to negotiate each case, in some cases giving in,
in others holding out.
Some companies doubt the worth of such an interventionist approach. In
particular, they argue there is little point in drawing up a detailed
corporate plan for the future and then attempting to train the people to fit
that plan. 'Five years ago we used to look at the business plan and then at
the people,' says Mike Haffenden, director of personnel at Hewlett-Packard
(UK). 'Now we don't know what the business plan is. So we help individuals
grow as people first.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P8741 Management Services.
</IN>
<XX>
