<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JAN 94 / Life policy agents say disclosure rules will cut business
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Telling potential customers the commission they will pay when they buy life
insurance will make them shop around and reduce life and pensions business
overall, says a survey of sales agents.
About one-third of tied agents - life company appointed representatives - in
the survey said they would leave the industry if commission disclosure
reduced their income. The survey also included independent financial
advisers and members of direct sales forces.
About three in 10 of the direct sales agents said they would leave the
industry if their income fell because of commission disclosure.
However, just over half of all those questioned said that if disclosure
reduced their income, they would fund their activities by increasing their
business and number of clients.
The poll was carried out in November and has been published by the Life
Insurance Association. It comes as the Treasury considers the draft rules
put forward by the Securities and Investments Board, the City's chief
watchdog, for requiring sales agents to disclose commission on life
products.
The new rules are expected to come into effect late this year.
The association said the responses to a questionnaire from 1,006 of its
members underlined the industry's concern that the proposals for disclosing
commission would not reflect a fair balance of the charges and expenses of
the different distribution channels for life products.
About two-thirds of respondents said they thought commission disclosure
would make clients shop around, mainly on the basis of cost, though this
view was less widely held among IFAs than among other categories of sales
agents.
Of those responding, 64 per cent thought the change would mean a reduction
in life and pensions business. A clear majority thought it would increase
the pressure for the client and sales agent to split the commission, a
practice known as 'rebating'.
Mr Lawrence Hawthorn, association president, said the survey reinforced the
industry's impression that disclosure could dilute people's commitment to
taking out cover.
</TEXT>
