<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JAN 94 / Tunnel prompts Stena to simplify ferry fares
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Competition on cross-Channel ferry routes will intensify today when Stena
Sealink announces a simplified fare structure modelled on the format adopted
by Eurotunnel, operator of the Channel tunnel, which is due to open in May.
Stena, which on Monday said it would wait until the official announcement of
Eurotunnel's tariffs next week, will today unveil its 1994 fare structure. A
standard return for a car and five passengers on the Dover-Calais route will
start at Pounds 126 rising to Pounds 220 in the peak season.
'The company is scrapping the traditional industry system of price bands
linked to sailing times in favour of a new simplified fares structure,' it
will tell travel agents at a presentation in London today.
'The old system was a way of fine-tuning our prices which had its merits but
it required a degree in statistical analysis to understand,' Stena says.
In future there is to be one price per day within four seasonal bands and
supplements for peak weekend travel. Ending the complicated tariffs will
make it easier for travel agents to sell tickets, the company says.
The standard return fare on the Dover-Calais route will be Pounds 126
between January and March, Pounds 188 from March to July, Pounds 220 from
July to September and Pounds 188 between September and December. This
represents an increase of 'a couple of per cent overall' on the 1993 fares,
it says.
Similar increases will be made on all of its seven routes to the Continent
and Ireland.
Stena says it does not intend to enter into a price war with Eurotunnel or
the other ferry operators. Eurotunnel might be able to charge a premium for
speed but it could not match ferry operators such as Stena with Pounds 60m
vessels offering a choice of restaurants and other facilities.
Eurotunnel is due to announce tariffs next Tuesday. It is expected to offer
return tickets of between Pounds 160 and Pounds 220 to Pounds 260 in the
summer, with premiums for busy weekends.
P&amp;O European Ferries said it would wait until Eurotunnel's formal
announcement before revealing its 1994 tariffs.
Eurotunnel funding, Page 16
</TEXT>
