FT  05 JAN 94 / Government accused of 'learning no lessons and doing very
little' over sinking of tanker Braer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government was accused yesterday of 'learning no lessons and doing very
little' as a result of the sinking of the tanker Braer in Shetland a year
ago today, James Buxton writes.
Mr Jim Wallace, Liberal Democrat MP for Orkney and Shetland, said the
government had refused to hold a public inquiry into the disaster, the
wreckage of which can still be seen off Garth Ness (above).
The government has yet to publish the report by the Marine Accident
Investigation Branch into the disaster and has refused to provide radar
surveillance of the channel between Shetland and Orkney. The inquiry on
marine safety around the British Isles has also yet to report.
The Liberian-registered Braer spilled 85,000 tonnes of crude oil when it
grounded. About 1,500 sea birds died but storms dispersed the oil. The
Shetland salmon farming industry lost about Pounds 20m because some fish
were contaminated and became unsaleable.
