<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JAN 94 / CBI and EEF halt merger move
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Confederation of British Industry and the Engineering Employers
Federation have dropped a controversial plan to merge their central
activities, but are to continue talking about co-operation.
The plan, which has been under discussion since the summer, would have
created the UK's largest single lobbying voice for manufacturing industry.
But it has fallen victim to opposition from the EEF's 14 powerful regional
associations.
Mr Nick de Jongh, the federation's director of external affairs, confirmed
yesterday that a merger of the two organisations' central functions was now
'off the agenda'.
But over the next few months the CBI and EEF will hold talks to identify
precise areas where they could work together to industry's advantage.
The CBI said: 'The talks are still continuing and we still expect some sort
of proposals to be formally put to the councils of both bodies in due
course. Until then, there is nothing further to add.'
Cancellation of the plan for a merger of the central parts of the two
organisations will come as a relief to staff at the much smaller EEF. But it
is likely to disappoint big companies, which would have had one fewer
organisation to join.
As a federation, the EEF could not have approved a merger without backing
from its regional associations, which provide a range of services to 5,000
member companies based on policies produced centrally.
Although the associations would have retained their identity, Mr de Jongh
said they were worried that policy might no longer be 'tailor-made' for the
engineering industry if the central functions of the EEF were subsumed into
the CBI or its National Manufacturing Council.
Both organisations had been hoping that a tie-up would enable them to lobby
more effectively and efficiently for industry. But Mr de Jongh said this was
still possible, as the EEF would be put on its mettle to identify when it
should work together with the CBI and when separately.
Some EEF functions could still be combined with counterparts at the CBI, he
said. 'But any change is likely to be evolutionary rather than
revolutionary. Our members did not want a 'big bang'.'
</TEXT>
