<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JAN 94 / Heathrow road link plan dropped
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
An Pounds 800m plan to improve road and rail links between Heathrow airport
and south-west London has been dropped by the government two months before
the end of the consultation deadline.
Mr Steven Norris, transport minister for London, said there had to be a
strong case for a plan which would mainly benefit local communities at a
time when there was pressure on public spending.
The Department of Transport would consider more limited measures if local
authorities were prepared to make suggestions, he said.
The decision was criticised by Movement for London, a pressure group headed
by the British Road Federation and including organisations such as the
Automobile Association, the Confederation of British Industry and the Road
Haulage Association.
It said: 'Government-appointed consultants have spent years and millions of
pounds looking at the problems of road and rail access to the world's
busiest airport. For the Department of Transport to reject proposals before
consultation has even finished is a disgrace.'
The group said transport problems around Heathrow were not a local issue and
were of strategic significance.
Consultants spent five years preparing a report that was published last
August. It recommended a new road link between the A3 at Kingston and
Heathrow, including a new Thames crossing, costing Pounds 580m. It also
proposed a rail link between Kingston, Heathrow and Waterloo station in
central London costing up to Pounds 250m.
The early decision to drop the plans was taken to end uncertainty, Mr Norris
said.
A Pounds 300m rail link between Heathrow and Paddington station in west
London is not affected by the decision. The service is due to start in 1997.
</TEXT>
