<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JAN 94 / Women managers progress faster than male counterparts
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Women who break through into top managerial posts possess attributes
enabling them to progress faster than their male counterparts, the British
Psychological Society's conference heard yesterday.
Mr Tuvio Melamed, a lecturer in occupational psychology at the University of
Central Lancashire in Preston, said women who rose above the 'glass ceiling'
managerial barrier had the sort of qualities that marked them out as top
executives.
However the price of success could be associated with a risk to mental
health. He said: 'The struggle of getting there makes them more introverted
and anxious than men because the environment in which they have to work is
so hostile.'
Mr Melamed said career success for men was related to qualities of extrovert
behaviour, dominance and confidence but this was not reflected in women
high-flyers. Women needed to be 'more men than men' but also needed to
fulfil additional criteria for success.
'Managerial women have to deal with extreme pressure and experience more
severe degrees of tension and instability than their male colleagues,' he
said.
</TEXT>
