FT  05 JAN 94 / Further delays for Iraq arms inquiry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Scott arms-for-Iraq inquiry faces further delays because of difficulties
in arranging the appearance of key witnesses, it emerged yesterday, Jimmy
Burns writes.
Public hearings are now expected to continue possibly into April, with
publication of the final report unlikely before the summer.
Lord Justice Scott began public hearings in May, and had hoped to begin
writing his report last month. The schedule was later revised so that the
hearings would end early this year.
Officials close to the inquiry blame the delays on the problems encountered
in securing ministerial support for a 'rolling programme' of witness
appearances.
Lord Justice Scott is understood to be particularly concerned by the
attitude towards his inquiry of Lord Trefgarne, a former defence and trade
minister, who has not replied to two separate questionnaires sent to him in
September and November. Lord Trefgarne said at the weekend that he would be
letting the judge know during the next two weeks whether he was prepared to
appear as a witness.
