<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JAN 94 / Recruiters 'rank honesty highly'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Small businesses place a far higher value on honesty, integrity and
enthusiasm for the job when recruiting young people and are less worried
about work experience or vocational and academic qualifications, a report
said yesterday.
The study's findings, reported at the British Psychological Society's
occupational psychology conference in Birmingham, appeared alongside other
research which showed that managers preferred job applicants to admit their
mistakes at an interview rather than blame their failings on others.
The study carried out on 498 small businesses by Hull University and Newland
Park Associates, a firm of occupational psychology consultants, investigated
selection methods used when companies were recruiting people under the age
of 20.
The researchers also found that companies in manufacturing and production
placed less emphasis on education and vocational qualifications than those
in the financial and business services sectors.
Many companies in the study were happy to recruit from initial telephone
inquiries or a 'knock on the door' rather than insisting upon written
applications. Job selection was based typically on a single unstructured
interview.
'The smaller the employer, the more they seem to rely on gut reaction and
first impressions,' said Professor David Bartram of Hull University, who
headed the study.
In a second report, Ms Jo Silvester, a Leeds University psychologist, told
the conference that job seekers who admitted their personal failings at
interviews were more likely to be successful than those who hid their
mistakes behind a veneer of perfection.
The research was based on tape-recorded interviews between employers and 45
undergraduates seeking jobs with a City law firm and a national distribution
company. Ms Silvester said: 'People who use excuses or pass the buck on to
others are actually seen as quite arrogant by interviewers and create a bad
impression.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6231 Security and Commodity Exchanges.
</IN>
