<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JAN 94 / World Trade News: Cash row may hit HK port extension
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE LUCAS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   HONG KONG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Expansion of Hong Kong's port, already hostage to approval from the Chinese,
faces further delay as the colony's government and private consortiums
building the new Container Terminal Nine (CT9) thrash out agreement on
funding and land availability.
Hongkong International Terminals (HIT), a subsidiary of Hutchison, and the
other Kwai Chung container terminal operators yesterday urged the government
to tackle outstanding problems, or risk capacity shortfalls of 1m TEUs
(20-ft equivalent units) by 1997.
Mr John Meredith, managing director of HIT, said the government should
allocate an additional 34 hectares of back-up land, which would let
HIT boost its capacity by 1m TEUs a year from its existing quay waterfront.
Mr Mark Leese, managing director of Modern Terminals, one of the three
contractors to the CT9 project, claimed the government was short-changing
operators on attached infrastructural work. Operators agreed to undertake
certain infrastructural work - for which the government is to reimburse them
 -in exchange for the development rights.
He claimed the actual cost of this work was HKDollars 3bn (Pounds 263m)
higher than government estimates, and said the discrepancy would be a hurdle
to reaching agreement.
