<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JAN 94 / Bank of France council chosen
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The six lay members of the monetary policy council of the newly independent
Bank of France were chosen last night after a brief disagreement between
Socialist president Francois Mitterrand and the conservative government,
Reuter reports from Paris.
The conservative prime minister, Mr Edouard Balladur, initially resisted Mr
Mitterrand's nomination of the former Socialist finance minister, Mr Michel
Sapin, but finally agreed. Two other nominees formally accepted were named
as Mr Michel Albert, chairman of the state-owned Assurances Generales de
France, and Mr Jean Boissonnat, a leading economics commentator. Officials
said three other candidates, whom they did not identify, had been more or
less agreed.
The six will join the Bank of France governor, Mr Jean-Claude Trichet, and
his two deputies on the council. The central bank was due to have become
autonomous on January 1, but the delay in naming the council has meant that
it does not yet have formal independent control of interest rates.
</TEXT>
