<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JAN 94 / US bank to pay Pounds 25m into Mirror Group fund: First
settlement lifts hopes of Maxwell pensioners
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Bank of America yesterday became the first financial institution to settle
claims stemming from the diversion of over Pounds 440m from pension schemes
controlled by the late Robert Maxwell, raising expectations that others will
follow.
The San Francisco-based bank said it had agreed to pay Pounds 25m, while not
admitting any liability, into the Mirror Group Pension Scheme.
'This has thrown the situation into a new realm where it may be possible to
talk about a settlement,' said an official at one investment bank alleged to
have helped divert pension scheme assets.
After receiving a writ in June 1992, Bank of America approached the pension
fund trustees about six months ago to discuss a settlement independently.
The writ alleged that Bank of America, which acted as a safekeeper for a
portfolio of securities, passed them to Credit Suisse on the instructions of
individuals who were not authorised to give such instructions.
The securities were later used as collateral for a loan to Mr Robert
Maxwell's private interests, the writ alleges.
Sir John Cuckney, appointed by the government to encourage financial
institutions holding pension scheme assets to return them, had no part in
the Bank of America move.
Mr Tom Brooks, Bank of America's assistant general counsel, said: 'We view
this settlement as an appropriate means of contributing to the restoration
of the pension funds without the delay and uncertainty to pensioners and the
bank of lengthy court proceedings, and of putting this claim by the trustees
behind us.'
The Mirror Group Pension Trustees had sought Pounds 38m from Bank of America
and Credit Suisse jointly. That case is scheduled to come to court in
October and the pension trustees said they will continue to seek the balance
of the funds plus accrued interest from Credit Suisse.
The writ also names Invesco MIM, Lehman Brothers International Ltd and
Capel-Cure Myers Capital Management. It seeks Pounds 200m, of which roughly
Pounds 50m relates to assets alleged to have been passed to Robert Maxwell's
private interests by the fund managers. The other Pounds 150m relates to
negligence charges for failing to inform the trustees of improper
activities. That case is due in court on January 25.
Mirror Group Newspapers has pledged to make up the shortfall from the
diversion of assets to its own pension scheme members.
It recorded a charge of Pounds 174m - to be paid over the lifetime of its
scheme members - in its interim report last June to cover this. The Bank of
America payment will reduce Mirror Group's liability by Pounds 25m.
Mr Colin Cornwell, chairman of Mirror Group Pension Trustees (MGPT), said he
hopes the Bank of America settlement will encourage others to seek a similar
solution. 'I think it makes sense commercially,' he said, noting that the
expense and adverse publicity of a public trial are likely to be damaging to
many financial institutions.
Yesterday, other financial institutions which handled assets missing from
the pension scheme said the Bank of America move had no bearing on their
cases.
Lehman Brothers said it was only prepared to consider a 'global settlement'
in which all financial institutions participate.
Coopers cleared in probe, Page 5
</TEXT>
