<DATE>940105
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JAN 94 / Money supply rise signals a strengthening recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Evidence that the UK economic recovery is picking up pace came yesterday
with a sharper-than-expected rise in the most narrow definition of the money
supply.
The Bank of England said M0 rose by a seasonally adjusted 5.8 per cent
year-on-year to December, supporting recent anecdotal evidence of an
excellent Christmas season for the retail sector.
The M0 measure consists of notes and coins in circulation, plus banks'
operational balances with the Bank of England. It is often a good indication
of activity in the retail sector.
The money supply figures did little to help sentiment in the UK government
bond market, where long gilt prices fell by 1 1/4 points. Analysts felt the
apparent buoyancy of the consumer sector may have dampened hopes of an early
cut in UK interest rates.
Gilts and equities were also affected by New Year profit-taking after strong
December rallies. The FT-SE 100 index, down 38 points at one stage, rallied
in the afternoon to close 9.9 points lower at 3,408.5.
The 1 per cent month-on-month rise in M0 was well ahead of market
expectations of a 0.4 per cent increase. However, the figure was partly
foreshadowed last week by a sharp rise in bank notes in circulation, which
rose an annual 7.1 per cent in the week to December 29.
The 5.8 per cent year-on-year rise in M0 compares with a 5.1 per cent
increase in the year to November. It is the highest since June 1990 and is
well outside the government's monitoring range of 0-4 per cent.
Yesterday's figures may have been distorted by temporary factors, such as a
relatively high level of operational bank deposits and a surprisingly high
rate of increase in Scottish and Northern Irish notes in circulation.
Also, the sheer scale of consumer spending at Christmas, and the pattern of
bank holidays, make the December M0 figures more volatile than other months.
The unadjusted figures showed a less significant annual rise of 5.5 per
cent, creating the possibility that there might be a problem with the
seasonal adjustments.
Mr Don Smith, UK economist at Greenwell Montagu, described the figures as
'erratic'. He said the market would monitor closely forthcoming figures on
December retail sales and on January notes-in-circulation for more
substantial evidence of the strength of consumer spending.
M0 is only one of the inflationary indicators studied by the government.
Others, such as M4, the broad money measure, are giving little sign of a
rise in inflation, although Nationwide's house price index, published
yesterday, showed a higher-than-expected 3.3 per cent annual increase.
But there was speculation that the M0 rise might dissuade the government
from making an early cut in base rates. Seasonally adjusted M0 has been
rising at 7.9 per cent, on an annualised basis, over the last three months.
'This is the first piece of hard evidence that points to strong retail
performance in December and that will push back the timing of a base rate
cut to February or March,' said Mr Simon Briscoe, UK economist at Warburg
Securities.
Sterling strengthened slightly against the D-Mark as traders felt an
imminent base rate cut had become less likely. The pound closed 0.6 pfennigs
higher at DM2.578 and gained a tenth of a cent to Dollars 1.4815. It also
gained a little further in New York.
House price rises Page 5
Lex Page 14
Gilts Page 21
World stocks Page 29
London stocks Page 32
