<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 94 / World Stock Markets (Asia Pacific): Region sees new records
set in eight centres
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Roundup
Eight markets saw new highs. Tokyo, Taiwan, Australia and New Zealand were
closed.
HONG KONG advanced 1.7 per cent, taking the Hang Seng index through the
12,000-point level to another record close as buy orders from overseas
institutions continued to pour in.
The index climbed 198.10 to 12,086.49. Continuing strong US demand was
particularly evident, helping to expand turnover to a heavy HKDollars 9.22bn
from Friday's HKDollars 7.36bn.
On the futures market the January index contract ended with a sizeable
premium to the physical market at 12,315, up 355 points.
Bank of East Asia, which will be among the first of the major banks to
announce its profits, climbed HKDollars 4.50 to HKDollars 57.50. Liu Chong
Hing was up HKDollars 2.20 at HKDollars 18.20 on expectations that it will
spin off its banking arm.
Sino Land jumped 80 cents to HKDollars 12.90 in active morning trade and
Tsim Sha Tsui Properties gained 70 cents at HKDollars 10.80 before they were
both suspended pending an announcement.
SINGAPORE saw strong retail demand, on expectations of more gains in coming
weeks, which took the Straits Times Industrial index up 15.85 to a peak
2,441.53.
Profit-taking was overwhelmed by a flood of new money. However, Rothmans
Industries plunged SDollars 1.20, or 11.9 per cent, to SDollars 9.70 when
the stock resumed trading after the announcement that plans for a regional
holding company were vetoed by its Malaysian associate.
KUALA LUMPUR registered further institutional and speculative buying and the
composite index advanced 13.53 to a record 1,288.86.
Rothmans fell MDollars 4.60, or 17.7 per cent, to MDollars 21.40 after the
merger proposal's rejection.
SEOUL saw buy orders which boosted financials and recent laggards such as
construction and low-priced counters, taking the composite index 13.14
higher to a peak of 879.32.
Blue chips were held back, however, by news that the Korea Securities Market
Stabilisation Fund planned to liquidate Won800bn of stocks later this month.
MANILA hit a new high as demand for blue chips kept the market up amid
profit-taking in other issues. The Composite index added 75.43 at 3,271.51.
JAKARTA edged ahead to a record close, the official index firming 0.88 to
589.65.
KARACHI, powered by strong demand for financials, polyesters and
pharmaceuticals, saw the KSE 100 index rise 7.89 to finish at a high of
2,178.09.
BOMBAY's 30-share index moved ahead 119.80, or 3.6 per cent, to a peak of
3,465.86 amid increased foreign buying on hopes for improved economic and
political stability in the coming year.
