<DATE>940104
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 94 / Emerging Markets: Wary eyes focus on bullish Asian markets -
The Emerging Investor
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALEXANDER NICOLL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Almost anybody who invested in emerging markets in 1993 will not be
regretting the decision. Spectacular increases in many markets were well in
excess of gains to be found in most developed countries. The combination of
rapidly growing economies, solid earnings growth, and weight of new money
was extraordinarily powerful.
But as the new year gets under way with a bang - eight Asian markets hit new
records yesterday - investors may ask how long the good times can go on.
Aren't emerging markets just a fad? Won't they soon come crashing down? Old
Asia hands might say that the only new factor in their region has been the
attention suddenly paid by foreign fund managers: dependably rapid
development has been under way in Asia for a long time - even China, of
which everybody wants to get a piece, has been reforming for over 15 years
now.
The suspicion that it's just a game to the fickle foreigners was fuelled in
1993 by pronouncements about China from Morgan Stanley, the US investment
bank. First it extolled China as the place to be (via Hong Kong). But a few
weeks later the portfolio weighting was reduced to below the level of before
the bullish remarks. What had appeared an important strategic statement
turned out to be a short-term, profitable play.
Apart from underlying fear that international cash will flow on into the
next investment wave, leaving emerging markets behind, there are signs
causing concern in some markets - such as an abnormally high level of retail
activity. Alarm bells should start ringing when brokers' analysis argues,
however plausibly, that normal standards for price/earnings ratios do not
apply because of the peculiarities of a particular market. Remember Japan?
How then should the investor approach emerging markets? A few points are
worth bearing in mind by the investor who wants to be sure of making a
strategic decision intended to bring benefits over the long term. The first
is that, as the word 'emerging' implies, the markets are not fully developed
and are thus more risky than those in the industrialised world. This does
not necessarily mean that the economic and political risks are greater,
though they may be. The markets are smaller, less liquid, more volatile.
They may be lacking in key areas of infrastructure: management of the stock
exchange and its settlement mechanisms, standards of regulation and
disclosure, transparency of corporate accounts, development of associated
financial markets, restrictions on foreign investors, and the taxation
system. Part of the investor's bet is that these handicaps will be removed
over time.
Second, the term 'emerging markets' covers a wide range of economies and
political systems. No two countries can be regarded as essentially the same,
even neighbours. Knowledge of individual countries - and of the companies
within them - is vital. So is an ability to step back and examine the wider
picture, analysing potential returns compared with other emerging as well as
developed markets. Like the markets themselves, the information flow about
emerging markets is still very much in the development stage.
The message from these points is that the ride is likely to be long and
bumpy. In exchange for greater risk and need for costly specialist
expertise, investors naturally expect a higher, sustained return. Rapid
rates of economic growth maintained over many years will help to provide
that.
But the effect of capital flows cannot be ignored. The plain fact is that,
until now, sharp price gains have been seen partly because the amounts of
foreign money, though perhaps quite small to the owners, are large for the
markets into which they have been flowing.
Baring Securities estimates that a net Dollars 38bn (Pounds 26bn) was
invested by foreigners in 1993 in the Pacific Rim (excluding Japan) and
Latin America, double the amount in 1992. It expects a modest increase to
Dollars 45bn in 1994. Even although it expects a tightening of US monetary
policy eventually to trigger a scaling back of US investment abroad, it
still forecasts that US investors will put Dollars 15-Dollars 20bn into
emerging markets this year. Nevertheless, it warns that 'it is prudent to
scale down exposure to those markets which have been fuelled exclusively by
foreign money of late.'
Salomon Brothers argues that pension funds, which it classifies as 'patient'
investors in contrast to those with 'hot' or 'momentum' money, are likely to
allocate a growing proportion of their growing pool to Asia. It says that
this new money is unlikely to be removed quickly and 'is a meaningful
proportion of the current free float of these markets and could rise to a
substantial percentage of the available equity.'
While this would aid confidence if it proved true, it still means that the
foreign investor who is in emerging markets for the long term has a problem.
The impact of the capital flow to which he is contributing is an important
factor in the strong performance of his portfolio. Only continued
development of emerging economies and markets can correct the imbalance. But
governments can help by allowing markets and the surrounding infrastructure
to develop so that foreign investors, with better information and security,
are less likely to pile out as quickly as they have piled in.
