<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 94 / Emerging Markets: News Round-up
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Taiwan
Taiwan's proposed stock capital gains tax is expected to have only a limited
impact on the bull run which saw the market rise by 80 per cent in 1993.
Mr Lin Chen-kuo, finance minister, has proposed a complex tax with different
rates for institutions and individual investors. If approved it would take
effect on July 1.
Pakistan
The privatisation commission is to offer 'a substantial number' of state
industrial enterprises for sale in the next two months and is also examining
the feasibility of privatising all public firms through the stock market.
South Korea
The Economic Planning Board has drawn up a reform plan to streamline
management of dozens of state companies through privatisations and mergers.
The EPB said 42 state-run and funded companies would be privatised between
1994 and 1997.
Indonesia
Mr Sanyoto Sastrowardoyo, investment minister, has said that domestic
companies can go overseas to list shares, selling up to a maximum of 30 per
cent of their stakes, as long as proceeds are to be reinvested in Indonesia.
Philippines
The merger of the rival Manila and Makati stock exchanges should be
completed this month, in spite of a sharp disagreement in financing a single
equities market.
Hong Kong
The Stock Exchange has said it will be more strict in enforcing rules
requiring stock issuers and their advisers to submit documents on time.
The exchange did not set new penalties for tardy compliance, but warned that
listings could be delayed.
