<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 94 / International Company News: Vote hits Rothman's E Asia
merger plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KIERAN COOKE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   KUALA LUMPUR
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Shares in the Malaysian subsidiary of Rothmans International, the British
tobacco giant, fell sharply on the Kuala Lumpur stock exchange yesterday
following a weekend vote by Malaysian shareholders rejecting a plan to merge
Rothmans operations in East Asia.
Rothmans of Pall Mall (Malaysia) shares, which opened at MDollars 26
(USDollars 9.70), closed down more than MDollars 4 at MDollars 21.40.
'There's a lot of speculation now about what Rothmans International intends
to do,' said a Kuala Lumpur broker. 'In the short term, shareholders in the
Malaysian company will see the value of their shares go down - but no one is
too upset at the moment.'
The shares have been trading strongly recently, rising from MDollars 13.50
last November.
Rothmans International had planned to merge subsidiaries in Malaysia and
Singapore with company operations elsewhere in East Asia. Rothmans planned
to use the combined financial muscle of the new company for a big marketing
drive in China and north-east Asia, where Rothmans still lags behind its
competitors.
While shareholders in the Rothmans subsidiary in Singapore voted for the
merger plan, Malaysian shareholders raised objections, saying that Rothmans
intended to take cash out of the highly profitable local unit to finance a
big marketing campaign in China and Japan.
Rothmans-made cigarettes now control about 55 per cent of the Malaysian
market.
In the year ending March 31 1993, Rothmans Malaysian and Singapore units
made a combined operating profit of Dollars 150.6m while Rothmans made
combined losses elsewhere in the region of Dollars 30.3m.
Permodalan Nasional (PNB), a state controlled investment company and one of
the biggest institutional shareholders in Rothmans (Malaysia) said it was
against the new plan because 'with the merger, the focus will . . . be
diverted to East Asia'.
Shareholders are now awaiting the next move by Rothmans International.
</TEXT>
