<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 94 / International Company News: Apple plans worldwide on-line
service
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TOM FOREMSKI
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Apple Computer, the personal computer maker, plans to develop a global
on-line service called eWorld that will be a key element in its strategy to
increase profits after a troubled year of layoffs and top management
changes.
The on-line service will be available in the US during the second quarter of
1994 and will be expanded to European and Asian markets later. Within five
years Apple expects eWorld to produce annual revenues of several hundred
million dollars and to attract several million subscribers.
Apple's eWorld will compete directly with market leaders Prodigy,
Compuserve, America Online and Genie. The on-line service will offer
different types of services and a special graphical user interface in which
users can more easily gain access to services and find information.
Almost all Apple Macintosh computers sold in 1994 will contain eWorld
communications software and a version for Windows systems will be available
at the end of 1994. Owners of Apple's hand-held Newton MessagePad system
will use eWorld to send electronic messages and to subscribe to news
services.
Apple declined to say how much it is investing in eWorld which will be
financed mostly from profits from the AppleLink on-line service which
generates annual revenues of about Dollars 32m and has 60,000 subscribers,
mostly software developers and Apple dealers. Mr Joshua Harris, on-line
services analyst at New York based consultancy Jupiter Communications, said
that Apple was late entering the market.
Sprint and British Telecom will provide Apple with communications links to
its data centre in Napa, California, which will host the on-line service.
Rival on-line services company American Online has licensed key software to
Apple as part of a cross-technology licensing agreement.
</TEXT>
