<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 94 / International Company News: De Crespigny hits a rough patch
 -A rare Australian corporate 'tall poppy'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRUCE JACQUES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Until last week, the corporate career of Mr Robert J. Champion de Crespigny
almost seemed to be fashioned by the gods. The Australian mining executive,
head of the flourishing Normandy Poseidon gold empire, rejoiced in the
oft-bestowed title of the country's only surviving entrepreneur.
The title has been well-earned. Since 1985, Mr de Crespigny has parlayed a
ADollars 500,000 position in an obscure Australian resource company into a
web of companies which are today capitalised at close to ADollars 5bn
(USDollars 3.3bn) and control annual gold production of well over 1m oz.
This heady growth record seemed set for another spurt in mid-December when a
Normandy offshoot launched a ADollars 260m takeover bid for Aztec Mining,
the Australian affiliate of Alumax, the US metals group. But just days
later, all was thrown into doubt with notification that Mr de Crespigny and
one of his former executives were to be charged by the Commonwealth Director
of Public Prosecutions.
Consistent with the aggressive style that has become his trademark, Mr de
Crespigny took the unusual step of foreshadowing the charges himself through
a note to the Australian Stock Exchange. The note said the charges would
allege that Mr de Crespigny and then fellow executive Mr Thomas Meiklejohn
failed to take reasonable steps to ensure that takeover documents delivered
in 1989 did not contain misleading information.
Mr de Crespigny maintains that he is innocent of the charges and will defend
them vigorously, but he admits they are bound to cause him 'enormous
personal damage'. So far, no charges have been formally laid, but commercial
judgment was swift, with initial falls in the share prices of most listed
entities in the Normandy Poseidon group.
Pronounced 'de krepney' and dubbed not so affectionately 'discrepancy' by
some of his gold industry rivals, Mr de Crespigny is one of the few
surviving corporate tall poppies in a land renowned for lopping them off.
No-one builds an empire like Normandy Poseidon without making some enemies.
Those on the receiving end of his many takeover forays have often accused Mr
de Crespigny of being a front for Anglo American, the South African mining
group. The Anglo group is Normandy Poseidon's biggest shareholder, with just
under 20 per cent of the capital.
But few realistically dispute that de Crespigny, with the title of executive
chairman, effectively controls the group with a personal interest of just 11
per cent. Other large shareholders include the AMP Society and the National
Mutual group, Australia's two largest investment institutions.
This structure forms the basis of another snipe from de Crespigny's rivals -
that he sits atop a convoluted corporate web much in the style of Mr John
Spalvins' failed Adsteam group, with control often based on interests of
less than 50 per cent.
Mr de Crespigny's aristocratic name is itself sufficient to make him an
oddity in the rough and tumble Australian mining industry. But his
aristocratic connections are distant. Mr de Crespigny's forbears lived in
Normandy, hence the name of his flagship company. His family migrated to
Australia via England in the 1850s, making Mr de Crespigny a
fifth-generation Australian and the first to move from the family base in
conservative Victoria to the racier atmosphere of Western Australia.
His group's current bid for Aztec has its ironies because Mr de Crespigny
got his start in the mining industry as that company's finance director
before going solo with a company called Amad.
Mr de Crespigny has always seen himself as a financial manager rather than a
miner or explorer. His companies have grown through takeover rather than
minerals discovery. He is seen as one of the most frugal managers in the
business, shrewd in hiring top resource specialists.
Among a string of corporate deals since 1985, two stand out as shaping
today's Normandy Poseidon. One was the successful raising of ADollars 114m
through equity issues just before the 1987 share crash. This financed the
purchase of Poseidon, the most enduring remnant of Australia's infamous
1969-70 nickel boom. Poseidon now controls some of the country's lowest cost
gold mines.
The other deal involved Mr de Crespigny in the ADollars 350m sale of some
key gold interests in 1987 to Mr Alan Bond, now a bankrupt. Mr de Crespigny
was able to repossess the assets because an ailing Bond group could not meet
the terms of the arrangement. This allowed Mr de Crespigny to emerge as a
pivotal stake holder in Kalgoorlie's Golden Mile, at the centre of
Australia's gold mining industry.
Mr de Crespigny has made a specialty of taking on some of the world's
leading mining houses in corporate battles. Apart from the current joust
with an Alumax associate, Mr de Crespigny has also locked horns with
Freeport McMoRan and Newmont of the US and Germany's Metallgesellschaft.
As if to show he is an all-rounder, Mr de Crespigny has also performed on
the defensive side, having fought off the unwanted attentions of TNT, the
Australian transport group.
</TEXT>
