<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 94 / Investors upbeat on US retail takeover
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Shares in Federated Department Stores rose by more than 10 per cent
yesterday as Wall Street reacted favourably to its plan to take over
troubled rival RH Macy through an unusual bankruptcy court manoeuvre
involving the purchase of Macy's debt.
Federated, with revenues of Dollars 7bn (Pounds 4.7bn) annually, operates
219 stores, including the up-market Bloomingdale's chain, and a takeover of
Macy's, best-known for its 111 stores of the same name, would create a
retailing colossus with annual sales of more than Dollars 13bn and
operations in most areas of the US.
Macy's has been operating under so-called Chapter 11 bankruptcy court
protection from its creditors since 1992 as it works on a plan of financial
reorganisation.
Federated, which itself emerged from bankruptcy protection last year,
announced on Sunday that it had acquired for Dollars 449.3m half of
Prudential Insurance Company of America's secured claim on Macy's. It has an
option to buy the remaining 50 per cent within three years.
The Prudential has been Macy's largest single creditor, and the deal
therefore gives Federated a significant say in the outcome of the company's
bankruptcy court reorganisation. Total claims against Macy's exceed Dollars
6bn.
Federated said it had acquired the claim 'with the ultimate objective of
working toward a combination of Federated and Macy's into a single,
nationwide, multi-billion dollar department store operation, with the
potential for greatly enhanced operating efficiencies'.
It is extremely unusual for a company to try to take over another by
acquiring its debt and pressing for a deal in bankruptcy court proceedings.
Mr Allen Questrom, chairman of Federated, said that 'none know better than
we that this will be a challenging process, with no guarantee that we will
be successful in accomplishing anything more than having made a sound
business investment'.
However, the debt deal also puts it in a strong position to block any bid
for Macy's from rival retail chains.
To succeed with a bid, Federated will need the support of Macy's other
leading creditors, such as the large fund management group Fidelity
Investments, as well as the judge overseeing the bankruptcy case.
Mr Myron Ullman, chairman of Macy's, said yesterday that it was still going
ahead with its own reorganisation plans and 'it would be inappropriate at
this juncture . . . to discuss with any particular creditor the role they
would play in our reorganisation'.
Shares in Federated closed at Dollars 23, up Dollars 2 1/4 , while Macy's
bonds also rose significantly.
</TEXT>
