<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 94 / Company News (This Week): Rival bidders weigh up final moves
 -Paramount
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The four-month Dollars 10bn (Pounds 6.7bn) takeover battle for Paramount
Communications, the film and publishing group, should reach a climax by
Friday, the last date for rival bidders Viacom and QVC Network to increase
their offers.
QVC, a cable television home shopping channel, has the edge. It is offering
Dollars 92 a share in cash for 51 per cent of Paramount's stock and a
mixture of securities for the remainder. Viacom, a cable television company,
is offering Dollars 85 a share in cash for 51 per cent, plus a blend of
securities.
However, Viacom is expected to announce a higher bid this week after
negotiations with two backers - Nynex and Blockbuster Entertainment. They
are believed to want improvements in the terms of their investment, as well
as a greater say in the running of Viacom-Paramount.
The central question is how much control Mr Sumner Redstone, chairman of
Viacom, is prepared to give up. The current takeover terms would leave him
with around 70 per cent of Viacom-Paramount's voting stock. He could boost
his bid by selling voting shares to partners.
Assuming Viacom bids again, QVC will have to decide whether to go still
higher. The stock market doubts it, since it has been depressing the share
price of whichever looks the victor. The winner, in other words, may be the
loser.
</TEXT>
