<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 94 / The Lex Column: International flows
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
As for international flows, much depends on the behaviour of US markets. A
striking aspect of last autumn's peak in the US bond market was that
equities continued to gain. This could be natural for this stage of the
cycle. If the bond market is rattled by the pace of the recovery, that
should be positive news for corporate earnings and therefore equities. If
the UK follows this pattern, equities should start outperforming gilts again
once a firm economic recovery brings a halt to base rate declines.
Yet the UK is much more dependent on international flows than the US, and
the risk remains that a market upset there will cause US investors to
retrench across the board. They, too, have been seeking to escape low
returns on cash, but even cash becomes attractive when other markets are
falling. With luck, the Federal Reserve will tighten just enough to preserve
the recovery while protecting the bond market from long-term inflation
worries. Such a soft landing would allow other markets to continue upwards.
But it requires delicate judgment as regards the timing and amount of any
interest rate rise. One false move and the reverberations would be felt
across the world. Then even the UK's relatively good economic prospects
would not protect its equity market from sharp correction.
</TEXT>
<XX>
