<PROFILE>_AN-EADCMAC4FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940104
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 94 / The Lex Column: Liquidity
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The nagging worry, though, is that such arguments are simply a justification
of a rise driven primarily by liquidity. Such a conclusion seems indicated
by the propensity of share prices to crumble when any leading company
announces disappointing profits. That was the fate of GEC and Hanson a month
ago. Beguiling as the re-rating argument is, there is also some underlying
nervousness.
Companies must produce some fancy earnings figures to justify present
multiples, especially in sectors such as building materials where economic
recovery has been most strongly discounted. Dividend growth is also unlikely
to keep pace with earnings, given the level to which cover sank during the
recession.
That may explain the appeal of utilities which can offer relatively
attractive yields and the prospect of some dividend growth. Banks have also
benefited because dividend cover is likely to grow particularly fast as
provisions come down after the recession. But the selectivity of investors
again suggests their primary aim is yield enhancement, against the
background of lingering scepticism about earnings.
Such worries will come to the fore if the economic recovery does falter as
taxes go up in the spring. Even then, though, the equity market could be
saved by further cuts in interest rates. Relative to cash the attraction of
equities would improve again, provoking further liquidation of retail bank
and building society deposits.
It is the switching of this money into equities and gilts coupled with large
inflows of foreign capital which sustained the market in 1993. The resulting
liquidity has not only enabled the government to fund its deficit at lower
and lower interest rates. It has also seen the equity market absorb more
than Pounds 11bn in rights issues and Pounds 5bn in new issues.
The central question for 1994 is to decide how long liquidity is likely to
stay abundant. On the domestic front the flow of retail cash may slow
somewhat, simply because the largest part of the fall in base rates has
already taken place. A combination of previous over-funding and tighter
fiscal policy will also substantially reduce the supply of gilts. The end to
pension holidays may create additional investment flows but these will be at
least partly offset by a fall in income available for reinvestment as
institutions are receiving smaller tax credits on their dividend income.
</TEXT>
<XX>
