<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 94 / Observer: Chips to Moscow
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Carlo de Benedetti, the Olivetti chairman, has been banging on for ages
about the company's move out of manufacturing into more profitable
computer-related services.
But Olivetti's latest deal, worth about L26bn - helping re-educate officers
of the Russian armed forces for civvy street - seems a radical move even for
him.
Olivetti won the contract from the European Commission. Along with German
and French partners it will provide management training to about 16,000 of
the 200,000-odd Russian officers deemed to be surplus to requirements since
the Berlin Wall came down. Some of the demobbed will even be shipped to
Europe for six months, to see western business at first hand.
De Benedetti's business savvy is justly renowned. Competitors are thus
asking themselves whether Olivetti's latest venture reflects hopes of
acquiring potential new staff, or is just a useful bit of advance networking
for future Russian sales.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Olivetti et Cie.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>ITZ  Italy, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
