<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 94 / Labour attacks tax rises as threat to recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Smith, the Labour leader, said yesterday that Britain's economic
recovery is likely to be hampered by tax increases due to take effect later
this year.
Mr Smith welcomed signs of 'modest' economic growth but he said forecasts
that the growth would accelerate failed to take account of the impact of tax
rises.
Mr Smith's comments signal the beginning of a new year opposition offensive
against the government's taxation policy, which Labour claims is 'unfair' to
the less well-off.
Labour leaders believe that the government is vulnerable to claims that both
Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, and Mr Norman Lamont, the former
chancellor, broke election promises not to increase taxes.
Mr Smith said: 'The Tories told us they would not increase taxes. They have
flagrantly broken this promise in the two Budgets of 1993 and the price is
going to have to be paid in 1994.
'They are huge increases, the biggest increases in British peacetime history
 -and this from a party that won the election in 1992 on the claims that it
would be a low-tax party.'
Mr Smith said that average families would face tax increases of Pounds 10 a
week from April and Pounds 16 a week from next year - equivalent to 7p on
income tax.
Public-sector workers would also face a pay freeze, amounting to an
effective cut in living standards and further draining demand from the
economy.
'I doubt very much if the impact of these tax increases has fully been taken
account of in some of the economic predictions which, of course, are pretty
varied,' he said.
Mr Smith urged the government to put the unemployed back to work by tackling
'the real problems' facing the economy - lack of investment, regional
development, skills and housing.
He urged the government to stimulate demand by allowing local authorities to
spend accumulated capital receipts. 'That would get people back to work and
would contribute to a virtuous recovery in the economy,' he said.
</TEXT>
