<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 94 / Purchasing managers upbeat about economy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Continuing expansion in manufacturing activity is confirmed by one of the
year's first economic indicators from the Chartered Institute of Purchasing
&amp; Supply today.
The institute's purchasing managers' index - which measures items including
output, new orders and delivery times - showed an increase in the rate of
manufacturing expansion for the third successive month. It stood at 54.6
last month, compared with 54.2 in November and 53.6 in October.
The institute's new orders index rose from 55.8 to 57.8 between November and
December reflecting, it says, sharp improvement in demand.
The south-east and East Anglia, which the analysis suggests suffered poor
growth between July and October, recorded the highest increase in new orders
last month.
Upward pressure on price levels remained relatively subdued in December,
according to the institute, which says its prices index rose to 51.5 in
November from 50.2, largely because of higher steel prices. Employment
levels were broadly unchanged, with equal numbers of companies recruiting
and shedding staff.
Two other reports published today predict relatively strong growth for the
economy this year. James Capel, the finance house, forecasts in its UK
Economics report that a modest acceleration in activity this year will
produce a 3 per cent increase in gross domestic product - the fastest growth
rate since 1988 - and similar growth next year.
Inflation is likely to remain very subdued in spite of the strengthening
recovery this year, the report suggests. It expects underlying inflation to
hover around 2.25 per cent for most of the year. It also predicts that base
rates will be cut to 4.5 per cent by the end of the first quarter.
Ernst &amp; Young's Item Club, in its forecast based on the Treasury model,
expects the economy to expand by an annual 2.5 per cent this year and next.
It warns that there is a risk of greater caution by consumers. It also warns
that a prolonged period of stagnation in continental Europe could reduce the
strength of recovery in the UK.
</TEXT>
