<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 94 / Shift work 'leads to health problems'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Many shiftworkers suffer sleeping and eating problems, the British
Psychological Society's occupational conference was told, Richard Donkin
writes.
A report by Mr Alexander Wedderburn of the department of business
organisation at Heriot-Watt Business School, Edinburgh, found that only the
hardiest of workers could easily tolerate shift work.
The study also found that some groups of workers were reluctant to adopt
eating and drinking habits that might improve their health. Shiftworkers,
who comprise one in eight of the working population, suffer more digestive
problems than day workers.
Mr Wedderburn said there were insufficient guidelines to help with the
problems.
</TEXT>
