<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 94 / Analysts predict PSBR will fall to Pounds 37bn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER and KEITH FRAY, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The chancellor's decision to raise taxes and cut public spending has led to
sharp revisions in the forecasts of 39 analysts surveyed by the FT last
month.
Mr Kenneth Clarke's measures, announced in the Budget, have convinced
economists from the City, academia and independent think tanks, that the
public-sector borrowing requirement will drop to about Pounds 37bn this
financial year and Pounds 30bn in the next. In the last FT survey, in the
spring, forecasters believed the PSBR would be Pounds 42.5bn in this
financial year.
Economists are sharply divided over what Mr Clarke's tactics will do to the
recovery, particularly in the spring when tax increases are introduced.
Mr Robin Aspinall, of Panmure Gordon, who has the highest forecast for
unemployment both this year and next, said: 'The Budget will stop it (the
recovery) dead in its tracks.'
Mr Gerard Lyons at DKB takes a similarly gloomy view. 'The Budget was too
tough,' he said. 'In view of the weak international environment I thought
the Budget was very risky, the biggest risk being that the savings ratio
remains high and consumer spending is weaker than the Treasury expects.'
Others are less downbeat. Mr Michael Saunders, of Salomon Brothers, said:
'The Budget will not have a dampening effect on growth, provided it is
offset by a long period of low interest rates.'
The state of the housing market also prompts contrasting views. Mr Alan
Davies, of Barclays Bank, said: 'The housing market recovery should
definitely gather momentum, boosted by pent-up demand, the fact that
affordability is at its lowest for several decades and the widespread
availability of fixed-rate mortgages.'
But Mr Richard Freeman and Mr David Thomas, of ICI, said that the slow
growth of real incomes and further cuts in mortgage interest tax relief
would 'retard any recovery' in the housing market.
Mr James Barty, of Morgan Grenfell, said: 'The housing market will not surge
in 1994. It is closely linked to real incomes and these will be squeezed.'
The vulnerability of the economy, according to many of those surveyed, is on
the consumer side. Mr Richard Jeffrey, of Charterhouse Tilney, said: 'The
most important figures to watch will be the monthly retail sales figures.
Should they begin to falter towards mid-1994, it will be a warning that the
recovery, itself, is under threat.'
Mr Peter Warburton, of Robert Fleming, who has the lowest forecasts for
consumer spending both this year and next, said: 'This Budget contains
little encouragement for employers to increase labour use or for households
to borrow more confidently. If neither employment nor credit growth has
revived in six months' time, then Mr Clarke will rue his single-minded
Budget.'
One surprise in the Budget was the Treasury's forecast for the current
account this year. It predicted that the deficit on the current account
would be Pounds 9.5bn this year, roughly half the deficit it was forecasting
in March. Many of the economists have followed suit, although the consensus
for this year is some Pounds 3bn higher than the official forecast.
Cambridge Econometrics, which has one of the lowest deficit forecasts for
this year and 1995 - Pounds 5.2bn and Pounds 1.8bn - expects a big
improvement in earnings from interest, profits and dividends. Indeed, a
sharp improvement in invisible earnings appears to be the assumption behind
most of the more optimistic forecasts for the current account.
But Mr Neil MacKinnon at Citibank said: 'Normally economic recovery is
associated with a widening trade gap. I see no reason to believe that the
balance of payments constraint has become a thing of the past.'
Both this year and next year, the consensus forecast for underlying
inflation - retail price inflation excluding mortgage interest payments -
falls within the government's target of 1 per cent to 4 per cent.
In line with the generally benign inflation forecasts, most of the
economists surveyed believe average earnings growth will remain subdued.
Average earnings - currently rising at a rate of 3 per cent - are forecast
to be growing by 3.9 per cent at the end of this year and 4.7 per cent by
the end of next.
Optimism here reflects pessimism on the jobs front. Even though unemployment
is falling, most economists clearly believe that the growth forecast for the
next two years will not be enough to make a significant dent in today's high
levels. Mr Peter Dixon, of DRI Europe, said: 'In 1994, better prospects
should lead to a pick-up in employment growth, but this will be constrained
by the need to restore margins.'
Mr David Kern, of National Westminster Bank, expects unemployment to fall to
2.5m by the end of 1995 and to remain above 2.2m during the remainder of
this decade.
Prof Wynne Godley of Cambridge University, who would normally have
contributed to the survey, was unable to take part because of work
commitments in the US.
</TEXT>
