<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 94 / Services seen as main job creators
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Employment growth will become more firmly established in 1994 and 1995, with
private-sector services leading the way, a report predicts today.
Cambridge Econometrics says in its latest Industry and the British Economy
report, that 206,000 jobs will be created in private-sector services in the
period. Much of the growth will come in business and miscellaneous services
 -including estate agents, recruitment, security, recreation, media,
dry-cleaning and hairdressing - which will produce an expected 141,000 jobs.
Professional services, among them accountancy, legal, architecture and
advertising, should contribute another 40,000, and hotels and catering
37,000.
In spite of these new jobs, the report warns that structural unemployment
will persist. It expects unemployment to still be 2.4m by the turn of the
century, and 2.2m by 2005.
The report expects the jobs growth in many service activities to be offset
by losses in transport, communications and the public sector. Many of the
new jobs will be in sectors characterised by a high ratio of part-time,
self-employed and female workers, while full-time, predominantly male jobs
will continue to disappear in manufacturing. Cambridge Econometrics expects
that another 68,000 manufacturing jobs will be lost by 1995.
GDP growth will, the report expects, strengthen from 2.1 per cent in 1993 to
2.6 per cent this year and 2.4 per cent in 1995. Growth this year will be
led by an upturn in investment spending, slightly stronger growth in
consumer expenditure and a continued positive contribution from net trade.
</TEXT>
