<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 94 / BT claims training saves Pounds 227m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
British Telecommunications has calculated that Pounds 7m spent on training
junior managers saves it Pounds 227m a year.
Two occupational specialists at BT have conducted what they say is one of
the first projects to quantify the savings achieved by training.
Mr Keith Coley, manager of competency, development and applications, and Mr
Geoff Lee, manager of management development processes, carried out a
three-year training evaluation which discovered that mistakes made by 159
junior managers cost the company Pounds 2m.
They said that a similar level of mistakes by the whole area of junior
management would have cost more than Pounds 227m.
In a report to the British Psychological Society annual occupational
psychology conference in Birmingham yesterday, the specialists said that
in-house training courses had raised performance to a level that earned the
company a further Pounds 71m on top of that which it would have lost through
poor performance.
Mr Coley said: 'At the time that we started this study we found no method
available which gave us a financial approach to the development of
training.' The formula they applied, they said, satisfied the company's
accountants.
The researchers said they assessed the direct costs of mistakes, the time
taken to rectify them, the indirect costs of time wasted and the costs of
loss of business. These were balanced against the added value of training
and its cost.
</TEXT>
