<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 94 / Portillo leads race for Tory chairman
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Michael Portillo, the rightwing chief secretary to the Treasury, emerged
yesterday as a leading candidate to replace Sir Norman Fowler as chairman of
the Conservative party.
Mr John Major, the prime minister, is understood to be considering four
candidates to replace Sir Norman when he stands down in the summer.
Mr Major would like the job to go to Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and
industry secretary, who is regarded as the government's best communicator,
in spite of a heart attack last year.
However, Mr Heseltine has told friends he is not interested in the job. He
wants to continue at trade and industry at least until the next elec-tion.
Mr Major's second choice is Mr David Hunt, the employment secretary, who is
a leading cabinet standard-bearer for the Conservative left. But Mr Hunt has
also let it be known that he would rather remain in a departmental post.
The reluctance of the two frontrunners leaves the field to Mr Portillo and
Mrs Gillian Shephard, the agriculture minister, who is seen as attractive to
women voters. Lord Archer, the novelist and former deputy party chairman,
would like the job, but is regarded as an outside candidate.
Mr Major has given Mr Portillo an opportunity to display his organisational
skills by putting him in charge of the Conservative campaigns in London and
the south-east for this year's local and European elections.
The government expects to be trounced in both elections. But the polls will
allow Mr Portillo to raise his public profile and demonstrate his
campaigning ability.
A better-than-expected result would provide a sound platform for promotion
to the party chairmanship, seen as a key role in the run-up to a general
election.
</TEXT>
