<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 94 / Unions attack utility chiefs' pay increases
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Unions yesterday attacked pay rises averaging more than 10 per cent for
senior executives of privatised utility companies last year.
Salary increases for the highest-paid directors of the privatised water, gas
and electricity companies averaged 13.9 per cent in the year to March 31
1993, but lower bonus payments pulled down the average increase to 10.8 per
cent, says Incomes Data Services, the independent research organisation.
Inflation was 3.5 per cent over the period.
The Trades Union Congress said yesterday that the increases would fuel the
growing sense of unfairness felt by public-sector workers.
The TUC estimates that the government's freeze of public-sector pay combined
with April's tax increases will result in public-sector workers facing cuts
of 6 per cent in living standards this year. Its figures assume a zero
increase in pay, a loss of 2.75p in the pound as a result of the tax
increases in last year's two budgets and a 3.35p loss because of inflation.
The January issue of the IDS Management Pay Review bases its findings on the
latest annual reports of the 10 water companies, 16 electricity companies
and British Gas.
The review says almost all the utility companies are largely complying with
the Cadbury committee's recommendations by separating salary and bonus
information for their top directors in annual reports.
IDS says pay growth was fastest in the water sector, where salary increases
for the highest-paid directors averaged 16.4 per cent. Total earnings rises
averaged 16.9 per cent.
In the electricity companies, salary increases for top executives averaged
12.7 per cent and the increase in total earnings averaged 8.1 per cent.
There were large variations in the figures. The highest-paid director at
Anglian Water had a 52 per cent rise in his total remuneration. In the year
to April last year he received a total package of Pounds 163,000 compared
with Pounds 107,000 in the previous 12 months.
However, a number of top directors saw their overall earnings fall. At
British Gas, the total package of Mr Robert Evans, the chairman, fell by
12.8 per cent. The main reason for this was that he relinquished his role as
chief executive and therefore received no bonus for the year.
Utility executive earnings are still nearly a fifth below the average of
directors of equivalently-sized private-sector firms.
IDS Management Pay Review. By subscription from IDS, 193 St John Street,
London EC1V 4LS.
</TEXT>
