<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 94 / Saudis to cut government spending 20%: Budget proposals
aimed at ending long period of pressure on currency
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBIN ALLEN and MARK NICHOLSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DUBAI, CAIRO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Saudi Arabia's promise to cut government spending by 20 per cent in 1994 has
eased pressure on the riyal and prompted a 1.5 percentage point fall in
interbank rates over the weekend.
The intended spending cut was the centrepiece of the kingdom's annual
budget, the outlines of which were unveiled at the weekend. It follows
several months of intensified international scrutiny of Saudi Arabia's
public finances, which have been in deficit for more than a decade but under
increased pressure with the recent softening of crude prices.
According to the budget statement, the government intends almost to balance
its books in 1994, with expenditure estimated at SR160bn (Pounds 28.7bn) and
revenues, mainly from oil sales, at SR155.6bn - a figure economists in
Riyadh said implied a price of Dollars 15 a barrel for Saudi Arabia's main
export crude and sustained output at present levels of 8m barrels a day.
The 1994 figures compare with a budgeted deficit in 1993 of SR27.8bn and
spending of SR196.5bn. However, the government has not published actual
figures for last year's overall revenues or expenditure, leaving the true
scale of the Saudi budget deficit a matter of conjecture. Some local
economists believe the easing of the oil price last year may have left a gap
as large as Dollars 15bn, while none believes the government to have met its
budgeted target.
Few other details of the 1994 budget were given at the weekend. There is, in
particular, no indication of how or where government spending cuts are to be
made, although the Saudi Press Agency said the king had banned the signing
of any new contracts which would add to spending in 1994.
King Fahd clearly hoped the announcement of intended spending cuts would end
pressure which has dogged the riyal over the past few months, while
banishing rumours of a possible devaluation.
The king told the council of ministers on January 1 he was determined to
maintain the riyal's present value. But while bankers and economists said
yesterday that pressure had eased on the Saudi currency, many expressed
caution before the London and New York financial markets returned to work
fully today.
Meanwhile, neighbouring Oman said it intended making a 10 per cent cut in
expenditure for 1994 over last year in its new year budget. The budget puts
spending at RO2bn (Pounds 3.5bn), of which 30 per cent is to on defence.
Revenue is estimated at RO1.7bn, leaving a deficit of RO301m.
Mr Qais Al Zawawi, deputy prime minister for financial and economic affairs,
said actual 1993 expenditure was Dollars 5.84bn (Pounds 3.94bn) and revenue
Dollars 4.4bn, leaving a deficit of Dollars 1.4bn. The actual 1992 budget
deficit came to Dollars 1.5bn, according to the central bank.
The government has not so far indicated how it arrived at higher 1994
revenues, though officials have previously indicated the government's
intention to sell some state-owned assets, including the Sultanate's only
oil refinery and the telecommunications agency, to the private sector.
Previous budget deficits have been funded by drawing down reserves and more
recently by issuing government development bonds, for which there has been a
ready domestic market.
Oman last year reached record oil output of 800,000 barrels a day, 96 per
cent of it from the majority state-owned Petroleum Development Oman.
However, PDO cut output by 5 per cent on Sunday in an attempt to help shore
up world prices.
</TEXT>
